South Korean President Roh Moo-Hyun called for a probe into illegal recordings involving the ambassador to the US and a Samsung executive in 1997.
The scandal led to the ambassador's resignation amid suspicions of involvement in a political slush fund scandal.
The National Intelligence Service was urged to investigate the case, which included discussions of illicit donations to politicians.
The spy agency apologized for wiretapping influential figures until 2002, causing public outrage.
The scandal highlighted deep-rooted corruption issues in South Korea, impacting political and business relationships.
Samsung Group considered legal action against media outlets for coverage of the scandal.
